(3) The same may be said of the verb subscribere. For- cellini quotes Macer Dig 48 2 8 qui duo iudicia adversus duos reos subscripta liabet. So also Cicero pro Cluentio ξ 131 in P Popilium subscripsit L Gellius, de invent ΙΙ ξ 58 quia parricidii causa subscripta esset, Plautus Poen 111 6 5 cras subscribam homini dicam, Pliny epp V 1 ξ 6 post ltoc ille cum ceteris sub- scripsit centumvirale iudicium, nou subscripsit mecum. The secondary sense is common ; compare for instance Velleius 11 60 ξ 5 Capito patruus meus A grippae subscripsit iu C Cassium.

(4) The substantive subscriptor likewise properly signifies a prosecutor or one who binds himself over to prosecute. Hence in div in Caec ξ 49 we read quartum quem sit habiturus non video, Caecilius counting as one. On this Halm aptly quotes fragm legis Serviliae* repetundarum ‘ tutum actorem et qui eum adiuvent alios subscriptores facito in contione iudicum iniuratorum'.

C. Repetundae.

Repetundae are thus defined by Sigonius (de iudiciis 11 27): repetundae pecuniae dictae sunt quas sive socii sive cives privati a magistratibus aut iudicibus aut publicis procuratoribus iudicio repetiverunt, quas illi aut in provincia aut in urbe aut obius dicendum aut ob iudicandum aut ob aliud aliquid publice curandum cepissent. That Roman citizens had the same right as allies to institute criminal proceedings de repetundis is abundantly proved by the fragments of the lex Acilia (on which 'See below), and is implied by Cicero when he says (div in Caecilium ξ 18) civibus cum sunt ereptae pecuniae civili sere
